Clean Data

To pre-process the vitals and lab results data before analysis, I converted the time_stamp to a POSIXct class and renamed the names of the vitals and labs. The vitals dataset now includes the following variables: subject (the patient id), name (the name of the lab/vital results), value (the numeric value of the result), and time_stamp (the time that the lab/vital was collected). As for the names of the labs included, we have: sbp (systolic blood pressure), dbp (diastolic blood pressure), hr (heart rate - beats per minute), resp_rate (respiratory rate - breaths per minute), and spo2 (oxygen levels). Finally, we removed any rows with NAs, or missing values.

vitals_clean <- vitals %>%
  mutate(
    time_stamp = ymd_hms(time_stamp),
    name = case_when(
      name == "vs_bp_noninvasive (s)" ~ "sbp",
      name == "s_bp_noninvasive (d)"  ~ "dbp",
      name == "vs_hr_hr"              ~ "hr",
      name == "xp_resp_rate_pt"       ~ "resp_rate",
      name == "xp_resp_spo2"          ~ "spo2",
      TRUE ~ name
    )
  ) %>%
  drop_na()

Feature Engineering

Distributional Summary Metrics

vitals_stats <- vitals_clean %>%
  group_by(subject, name) %>%
  summarise(
    mean = mean(value),
    sd   = sd(value),
    iqr = IQR(value),
    skewness   = skewness(value, type = 2),
    .groups    = "drop"
  ) 


vitals_stats_wide <- vitals_stats %>%
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = subject,
    names_from = name,
    values_from = c(mean, sd, iqr, skewness),
    names_glue = "{.value}_{name}"
  )
baseline_vitals_stats_joined <- sqldf("
  SELECT
    b.*,
    v.*
  FROM baselines b
  LEFT JOIN vitals_stats_wide v
    ON b.mrn = v.subject
")

Temporal Dynamics

library(slider)

temporal <- vitals_clean %>%
    arrange(subject, name, time_stamp) %>%
    group_by(subject, name) %>%
    mutate(
      time_num = as.numeric(time_stamp),  # seconds since epoch
      roll_sd  = slide_dbl(
        value,
        sd,
        .before = 3 - 1,
        .complete = TRUE
      )
    ) %>%
    summarise(
      # Direction of change / trend
      slope = if (n() >= 2)
        coef(lm(value ~ time_num))[2]
      else NA_real_,

      # Net shift
      net_shift = last(value) - first(value),

      # Volatility
      vol_mean = mean(roll_sd, na.rm = TRUE),

      # Optional extras (often useful)
      
      first_value = first(value),
      last_value  = last(value),

      .groups = "drop"
    )
temporal_wide <- temporal %>%
  pivot_wider(
    id_cols = subject,
    names_from = name,
    values_from = c(slope, net_shift, vol_mean),
    names_glue = "{.value}_{name}"
  )
temporal_joined <- sqldf("
  SELECT
    s.*,
    t.*
  FROM baseline_vitals_stats_joined s
  LEFT JOIN temporal_wide t
    ON s.subject = t.subject
")

Clinically Anchored Metrics

Blood Pressure Category Systolic and Diastolic Pressure (mm Hg) Normal Less than 120 systolic pressure AND Less than 80 diastolic pressure Elevated 120 to 129 systolic pressure AND Less than 80 diastolic pressure High Blood Pressure Stage 1 130 to 139 systolic pressure OR 80 to 89 diastolic pressure High Blood Pressure Stage 2 140 or higher systolic pressure OR 90 or higher diastolic pressure Hypertensive Crisis Higher than 180 systolic pressure OR Higher than 120 diastolic pressure Contact your provider immediately.

A normal heart rate (at rest) is 60 to 100 beats per minute. (https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/diseases/16749-arrhythmia)

The normal respiratory rate for an adult at rest is from 12 to 20 breaths per minute. A respiratory rate under 12 or over 25 breaths per minute is cause for concern. (https://www.lung.org/blog/respiratory-rate-vital-signs).

QDA.error <- function(Train, Test){
  qda.out <- qda(event ~ .,data=Train)
  pred.class = predict(qda.out,Test)$event
  mean(pred.class != Test$event)
}

PickBest <- function(X, p) {
  # Convert event factor ("No"/"Yes") to numeric 0/1
  y <- as.numeric(X$event == "Yes")

  # Compute correlations
  correlations <- numeric(p)
  for (i in 26:p) {
    correlations[i] <- cor(X[, i], y, use = "complete.obs")
  }

  # Sort variables by absolute correlation (better for selection)
  sorted <- data.frame(
    Variable = names(X)[1:p],
    Cor = correlations
  ) %>%
    dplyr::arrange(desc(abs(Cor)))

  # Return top 20 variable names
  sorted$Variable[1:20]
}
best20 <- PickBest(train_data, p=61)

Classification Tree

# Fit a classification tree on the training set using Gini impurity
mytree <- tree(event ~ ., data = train_data, split = "gini")

# Run 10-fold cross-validation on the training tree using misclassification pruning
mytree.cv <- cv.tree(mytree, FUN=prune.misclass, K=10)

# Plot cross-validated deviance (error) as a function of tree size
plot(mytree.cv$size, mytree.cv$dev, type = "b")
# Highlight the size(s) that achieve the minimum CV deviance in red
points(
  x = mytree.cv$size[mytree.cv$dev == min(mytree.cv$dev)],
  y = rep(min(mytree.cv$dev), sum(mytree.cv$dev == min(mytree.cv$dev))),
  col = "red", pch = 19
)

# Prune the original tree to the optimal size determined from cross-validation
final.tree = prune.tree(mytree, best = mytree.cv$size[mytree.cv$dev == min(mytree.cv$dev)])
## Warning in best <= size: longer object length is not a multiple of shorter
## object length
# TODO: Visualize the pruned (final) tree with split points and predicted class labels
plot(final.tree); text(final.tree, pretty = 0)

# Generate class predictions on the test set using the pruned tree
mypredict=predict(final.tree, newdata=test_data, type="class")

# Create a confusion matrix comparing predicted vs. actual classes
tmp=table(Predicted = mypredict, Actual = test_data$event)
